<DOC><DOCNO> AP880724-0011 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 0949EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w BC-EmbassyFire     07-24 0194</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Embassy Fire,190</SECOND><HEAD>Officials Investigating Fires At Madagascar Embassy</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two fires broke out at the Madagascan Embassyearly Sunday.   Lt. Ransom Washington, spokesman for the District of ColumbiaFire Department, said officials were investigating a fire thatoccurred at 2:17 a.m. EDT and a second fire that erupted about twohours later.   ``I smelled the smoke of the fire, so I decided to awaken myfamily,'' said Leon M. Rajaobelina, the ambassador from Madagascar.``We called immediately the Secret Service and within a minute theywere there, and the fire department was there within five minutes.''   Battalion Chief Dennis Boatman, who was at the scene of thefirst fire, said firefighters worked for about 10 minutes to bringthe blaze under control.   Fire officials told the ambassador and his staff that the blazestarted in the reception area of the building. JocelynRafidinarivo, the embassy's counselor for public affairs, said thefire may have been started by a lit cigarette.   The fire department spokesman said he did not know if the secondfire occurred in the same room.   No injuries were reported in either fire. Damage estimates werenot available.</TEXT></DOC>